me for a maker of leather bottles, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bouteille</i> ‘bottle’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":102,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Boteler was born in Bedfordshire, England as the daughter of John Boteler and Elizabeth Sutton. She married John De Broughton about 1370, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 11 October 1399, in England, and was buried in Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–11 October 1399":"–11. oktoober 1399","–1399":"–1399","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1365–1447":"1365–1447","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1300–1334":"1300–1334","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1447":"1447","1403":"1403","1334":"1334","abt.  1370":"umbes 1370","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1310":"1310","11 October 1399":"11. oktoober 1399","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–11 October 1399":"–11. lokakuuta 1399","–1399":"–1399","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1365–1447":"1365–1447","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1300–1334":"1300–1334","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1447":"1447","1403":"1403","1334":"1334","abt.  1370":"noin 1370","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1310":